- Metal programming â€” [[February 8th, 2026]]
    - Create a Swift executable project, then you can start doing API operations after grabbing a GPU device from `MTLCreateSystemDefaultDevice()`.
    - Graphics API is simple, similar to WebGPU.
        - `device.makeBuffer()` - creates a sized GPU buffer, you can access the pointer
        - `buffer.contents().bindMemory()` - view the buffer as a mutable array (note: Apple has unified memory so you can just write directly to the array)
        - `SIMD2<Float>` is like a `vec2<f32>` type.
        - `device.makeCommandQueue()` - create a command queue (stream) for op dispatch, similar to a CUDA stream, each runs operations asynchronously
        - `commandQueue.makeCommandBuffer()` - create a set of commands
            - `commandBuffer.makeBlitCommandEncoder()` - copy data between buffers
            - `commandBuffer.makeComputeCommandEncoder()`
            - `commandBuffer.makeRenderCommandEncoder()`
            - `commandBuffer.addCompletedHandler { ... }` - run when it is done
            - `commandBuffer.commit()` - dispatch instructions to GPU
            - `commandBuffer.waitUntilCompleted()` - synchronously block until done
        - MTKView - subclass of the View in AppKit / UIKit
        - `kernel` refers to compute pipelines, they are dispatched in grids of threadgroups, similar programming model to CUDA.
